<header class="header">
  <h1>Best Pollination Bags for Pepper Seed Saving</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Saving true pepper seed depends on isolating flowers before they open.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>For most gardeners, the best pollination bags for peppers are breathable, fine-mesh bags that prevent insect access while allowing airflow.</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    Peppers are often self-pollinating, but insects can still cause cross-pollination between varieties. If you want to save seeds that grow true to type, you need to isolate the flowers before they are pollinated.
  </p>
  <p>
    Pollination bags make that possible by creating a physical barrier around the flower cluster.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Quick Answer: What Works Best?</h2>

  <div class="quickAnswerBox">
    <ul class="plainList">
      <li><strong>Best overall:</strong> fine mesh, breathable bags.</li>
      <li><strong>Best size:</strong> large enough to cover flower clusters.</li>
      <li><strong>Best feature:</strong> secure closure to block insects.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>
    Airflow matters just as much as insect exclusion.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Pollination Bags Are Needed for Peppers</h2>

  <p>
    While peppers can self-pollinate, insects like bees can transfer pollen between plants. This leads to mixed genetics in saved seeds.
  </p>

  <p>
    Pollination bags prevent insects from reaching the flowers while still allowing natural pollination within the plant.
  </p>

  <p>
    This ensures seeds remain true to the parent variety.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Makes a Good Pollination Bag</h2>

  <h3>Fine Mesh</h3>
  <p>
    Small openings prevent insects from entering while allowing air circulation.
  </p>

  <h3>Breathability</h3>
  <p>
    Reduces moisture buildup and prevents overheating.
  </p>

  <h3>Secure Closure</h3>
  <p>
    Drawstrings or ties keep the bag sealed around the stem.
  </p>

  <h3>Reusable Material</h3>
  <p>
    Durable bags can be used across multiple seasons.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>When to Apply Pollination Bags</h2>

  <p>
    Bags should be placed over flower buds before they open. Once pollination has already occurred, isolation is no longer effective.
  </p>

  <p>
    Timing is critical for seed purity.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How to Use Pollination Bags for Peppers</h2>

  <ol class="plainList">
    <li>Select a healthy flower cluster.</li>
    <li>Place the bag over unopened buds.</li>
    <li>Secure the closure around the stem.</li>
    <li>Leave the bag in place until fruit begins to form.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    Once fruit sets, the bag can often be removed.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Get Wrong</h2>

  <h3>Applying Bags Too Late</h3>
  <p>
    Pollination may already have occurred.
  </p>

  <h3>Using Non-Breathable Materials</h3>
  <p>
    This can trap moisture and damage flowers.
  </p>

  <h3>Leaving Gaps in the Seal</h3>
  <p>
    Even small openings allow insects inside.
  </p>

  <h3>Using Bags That Are Too Small</h3>
  <p>
    Restricts growth and damages flowers.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How This Fits Into Seed Saving</h2>

  <p>
    Pollination bags are part of a larger seed-saving process that includes plant selection, labeling, and proper harvesting.
  </p>

  <p>
    Isolation ensures the genetic consistency of future plants.
  </p>
</section>

